  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka stocks dip in mid-day trade as fuel shortage continues",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka\u2019s shares fell over 1.7 percent within the first hour of trade dragged down by weak investor sentiments as the fuel shortage continues in the country, market participants said.",
        "The main All Share Price Index fell 1.72 percent or 128.21 points to 7,323.70 at 1135 hours on June 28.",
        "\u201cLast week, we saw the market gaining for four straight sessions solely on the news that a fuel shipment was due to arrive on June 24th however now the country is unsure when it will receive its next fuel shipment,\u201d a top market analyst said.",
        "\u201cTherefore unless there is a confirmation on the fuel supply I feel the market will continue to fall or move sideways. There are no other factors in the market for it to move up either.\u201d",
        "The most liquid index S&P SL20 slipped 1.74 percent or 41.37 points to 2,339.72.",
        "Top losers were Expolanka, Aitken Spence and Browns Investment. (Colombo/June28/2022)"
      ],
